NS Covid Rates

Gordon Shotwell

01 April, 2020

Data

The data comes from daily reports from the Nova Scotia Government which I record in a Github Repo.

The first plot is a plot of total positive tests over time. The red line shows a 35% daily growth rate, which is about what wouldve happened had we not undertaken any public policy interventions. The black line is the actual cases.

I stole this plot from an excellent data visualization of covid trends. Each point is a day and it shows the sum of new cases in the previous five days against the number of total cases. I chose a five day sum because thats about the mean incubation period for COVID-19.

Tests

Next we look at tests. The first one shows how great the microbiology lab has been in ramping up testing capacity. This is incredible and they deserve a great deal of thanks from all of us. I would be sending gift baskets of home made saurkraut and miso if that didnt violate social distancing rules.

The last thing to look at is the positive rate for our testing. This should be read in conjunction with the previous chart because if we test a lot of people, the positive rate will probably go down even though nothing changed about the disease. The thing to pay attention here is if these two move in the same direction, if the number of tests goes up and the positive rate also goes up thats bad, if they both go down thats good.
